english:
  title: Inscription and Preface for the Paintings Presented to the Gui Valley Academy
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Four scrolls in all: Bodhidharma Crossing the River with a Reed, Samantabhadra with the Elephant and Young Acolyte, and the Large Characters reading 'Awakening Cloud' and 'Gui Valley'—equal in height and width, all bearing the sovereign's own brush.

    Now the Great Master Yun of the Cao Stream Sect, who holds the title of Master of the Dharma Teaching and Keeper of the True Teachings, carried these paintings to Han Mountain to show Lee Saek, saying: "To honor the sovereign's gift, nothing surpasses writing. For this displays it to the present world and transmits it to generations hence; there is no other way. Therefore I seek a scholar's hand to write the encomium. Will you not do this honor?"

    He continued: "The Long Reed and White Elephant paintings serve to admonish one such as I. The sovereign's compassion knows no bounds. Awakening Cloud is my name; Gui Valley is my personal name. Of the tens of thousands who have left the world to study the Way, how many have their names reach the sovereign's ear? And to have them inscribed in such magnificent characters, illuminated for all this age to behold—what fortune could exceed this? Thus do I entrust this entirely to you."

    I, your servant Saek, humbly receive and unfold these scrolls. Afterward, I reflect:

    Buddhism has long held honored place in the world. Yet those who speak merely of cause and effect, of crime and reward, touch only the surface. But those who dwell in the high and void, standing alone beyond the ten thousand things—even we Confucian scholars of lofty aspiration cannot help but honor them. Respectfully I consider: His Sacred Majesty has deeply grasped the subtle meaning, and in taking from them, he obtains their true Way. Thus does he sweep away the corruptions of recent times and restore the ancient virtue of our founding sage. Yet Gui Valley alone has received such favor—granted honorific names of praise, and in moments of leisure, the sovereign remembers him still, extending his own brush and seal in such tokens of affection. By this we know what manner of person he must be.

    Gui Valley comes from a noble lineage. His nature was never common, and his cultivation through learning has become refined. Thus does he embody the mind of Bodhidharma and walk the path of Samantabhadra. In his name lies the principle: no-mind as the source of all being. In his epithet lies the truth: the Six Storages as the root of all action. His conduct flows naturally; his heart rests clear. He is one who no longer holds things as things.

    That he receives this day's bestowal is no mere chance—it is fitting.

    The great characters are deep and steady, weighty as a bronze vessel of ten thousand pounds. Their transformations shift like cinnabar refined nine times. The elephant's gait falls heavy and measured; river winds fill the robes. All human emotion, all the forms of things, reach their perfection here. The sage's heart speaks through the brush as the Creator's handiwork manifests in matter.

    I humbly bow and place my forehead to the ground, offering this verse:

    *Gui Valley's harmonious spirit dwells in Heaven; its luminous emptiness resides in things. It holds fast to the subtle workings of the Way, unobstructed and flowing. Who shall disperse this equally that the Six Directions become One?*

    *Bodhidharma's body—emptiness itself; sky and water share one light. Distant, receding, the wind grows clear, the moon bright. In that vastness, what small thing persists? Only the unchanging—that which cannot be known.*

    *Samantabhadra on his six-tusked elephant strides across the great plain. Magnificent! Glorious! Yet on the mountain path, my carriage alone continues its journey.*

    *By the dharma name No-Mind, I make mind itself. I enter and exit the Great Void. Wind becomes my companion, rain my son. Such diligence! Who but a master could fathom this sublime mystery?*
  footnotes:
    - Bodhidharma and Samantabhadra are central figures in East Asian Buddhism, representing respectively the transmission of sudden enlightenment and the practice of the bodhisattva path.
    - The 'Six Storages' (藏六) likely refers to the six sense organs or the treasury of dharma, representing the hidden depths of Buddhist realization.
    - Lee Saek skillfully weaves Buddhist imagery with Confucian virtue, suggesting that the highest spiritual cultivation transcends sectarian boundaries.
